  "text": "Dennison et al www.clinicalobgyn.com be particularly elevated among children in whom growth of the skeletal envelope is forced ahead of the capacity to mineralize, a phenomenon which is accelerated during pubertal growth. A second paper from this cohort has identified a low BMI in childhood as an important predictor of hip fracture in adulthood, suggesting a direct effect of low fat mass on bone mineralization, or an influence of altered timing of pubertal maturation. [CITATION_1] The third piece of epidemiological evidence that osteoporosis might be programmed stems from mother-offspring studies.",
